      title: "In-Stock Probability & Fill Rate",
      icon: "\uD83D\uDCE6",
      body: "Two ways to set order quantities:<br><br><strong>1. Profit maximization:</strong> CR = C<sub>u</sub> / (C<sub>u</sub> + C<sub>o</sub>) &rarr; find z* from &Phi;(z*) = CR<br><br><strong>2. Service level target:</strong> Choose Q* so that Pr(Demand &le; Q*) = target service level<br>&bull; e.g., 95% in-stock &rarr; &Phi;(z*) = 0.95 &rarr; z* = 1.65<br>&bull; Q* = &mu; + z* &times; &sigma;<br><br>The service-level approach is used when stockout consequences are hard to quantify (e.g., patient safety, reputation) or when a firm commits to a service guarantee.<br><br><strong>In-stock probability vs. Fill rate:</strong> In-stock probability = Pr(all demand met) = Pr(D &le; Q). Fill rate = E[Sales]/&mu; = fraction of demand fulfilled on average. Fill rate is always &ge; in-stock probability, because even when you stock out, you still serve most of the demand."
